title: Make ORT callable from various Pytorch compilers (LazyTensor, TorchDynamo, etc)
body:
A Pytorch backend is a program which is responsible for Pytorch's actual computation. For example, if you register a new GPU backend, Pytorch may call that backend for GPU computation. [torch_xla](https://pytorch.org/xla/release/1.9/index.html) provides an innovative mechanism of adding Pytorch backend. Comparing with [eager mode backend](https://pytorch.org/tutorials/advanced/extend_dispatcher.html#what-s-a-new-backend), [torch_xla](https://pytorch.org/xla/release/1.9/index.html) captures bigger graphs before invoking computation. Pytorch community is actively working on extending [torch_xla](https://pytorch.org/xla/release/1.9/index.html) framework to support custom backend. This PR demonstrates how to add ORT as one of them.

Highlights: with this PR, 
- ORT can capture computation from torch.jit, torch.fx, normal Pytorch computation (e.g., calling `torch.mul` and an `nn.Module`).
- Unsupported computation is automatically done in Pytorch, so no fallback is required in our code.

Features implemented:
- Various tensor types are supported.
- CPU and GPU mode.
- Session caching. We reuse session if input schema is the same.
- No memory copy when exchanging tensors between ORT and Pytorch.

From the test script below, we show that no model code change is needed when enabling this feature.
```python
import itertools
import torch

# Lines to set ORT as a new backend
import lazy_tensor_core
from onnxruntime.capi import _pybind_state as ost
import lazy_tensor_core.core.lazy_model as ltm
ost.register_ort_as_torch_jit_executor()
lazy_tensor_core._LAZYC._ltc_init_ts_backend()

def model(x):
    y = x * x
    z = y + x
    p = z * x
    q = p - x
    r = q / x
    return r

def run_forward(tag, x):
    y = model(x)
    ltm.mark_step()
    return y


def run_forward_backward(tag, x):
    assert x.requires_grad
    y = run_forward(tag, x)
    y.sum().backward()
    ltm.mark_step()
    return y, x.grad

def run(x, dtype, can_run_backward):
    baseline_device = 'cpu'
    checked_device = 'lazy'
    x_cpu = torch.tensor(x, device=baseline_device, dtype=dtype)
    x_lazy = torch.tensor(x, device=checked_device, dtype=dtype)

    expected = run_forward(baseline_device, x_cpu)
    generated = run_forward(checked_device, x_lazy)
    torch.allclose(expected, generated.to(baseline_device))

    if not can_run_backward:
      return

    expected, expected_grad = run_forward_backward(baseline_device, x_cpu.requires_grad_())
    generated, generated_grad = run_forward_backward(checked_device, x_lazy.requires_grad_())
    torch.allclose(expected, generated.to(baseline_device))
    torch.allclose(expected_grad, generated_grad.to(baseline_device))

x_floats = [-1.0, 1, [-1.0, 1.0, 2.0], [-0.0, 0.0, 7.0]]
x_ints = [[1, -1], [2, 1], [-2, -2]]
float_types = [torch.float64, torch.float, torch.float16]
int_types = [torch.int64, torch.int32]

# Test float types.
for x, dtype in itertools.product(x_floats, float_types):
  run(x, dtype, can_run_backward=True)

# Test int types.
for x, dtype in itertools.product(x_ints, int_types):
  run(x, dtype, can_run_backward=False)
```

Steps to build Pytorch LazyTensor
1. Clone Pytorch master branch
2. cd pytorch
3. python setup.py clean

title: PropagateCastOps uses and modifies 3 global containers at runtime
body:
**Describe the bug**
`PropagateCastOps` transformer makes use of 3 global containers at runtime. This presents a risk that two or more models being loaded at the same time can have side effects on each other's optimizations as different instances of the transformer modify the same global structures. This may also result in data corruption. Specific containers in question:
* [fp16_allow_ops](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/ef7b4dc05cae1084546ff7caba048a2f908ac1d8/onnxruntime/core/optimizer/propagate_cast_ops.cc#L72) cleared and populated at construction time
* [inserted_node_names](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/ef7b4dc05cae1084546ff7caba048a2f908ac1d8/onnxruntime/core/optimizer/propagate_cast_ops.cc#L103) used at runtime and cleared at the end of each run
* [converted_node_names](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/ef7b4dc05cae1084546ff7caba048a2f908ac1d8/onnxruntime/core/optimizer/propagate_cast_ops.cc#L104)  used at runtime and cleared at the end of each run

**Description**
Update QDQ propagation transformer to insert new QDQ nodes instead of moving the existing one. This creates a more consistent `DQ -> op -> Q` pattern for other components to recognize.
Upgrade this transformer to a basic level optimization as it yields a valid ONNX graph.

title: Fix incorrect type constraint registration for operator kernels.
body:
**Description**: 
Fix incorrect type constraint registration for RoiAlign. This led to the input type not actually being checked when matching a kernel as the invalid constraint name is treated as a missing optional input. This also means no model has every actually used RoiAlign with 'double' input. 

Also fix missing dependency for the unit test exe. Whilst it doesn't link against the CUDA providers lib, without the dependency VS doesn't know it needs to rebuild the library if there are changes.

After a check for invalid constraints was added a number of other invalid registrations were found. Update those kernel registrations as an invalid constraint means no checking during kernel matching. As there are a number of different ways in which the registration was invalid there was no easy way to keep a stable hash for the existing kernels. Due to that, add a hash replacement mechanism so we can provide backwards compatibility for existing ORT format models that use any of the affected kernels.

**Motivation and Context**
#10046
Fixing invalid registrations so the kernel matching enforces the expected constraints.

**Describe the bug**
It seems like the output of the `ReduceMax` Operator when feeding NaN values depends on the number of NaN values.
I noticed that `ReduceMax` behaves like the following:
```
ReduceMax([NaN, NaN, x]) => NaN
ReduceMax([NaN, NaN, NaN, x]) => x
ReduceMax([NaN, NaN, NaN, NaN, x]) => NaN
```

```
import onnx
```

title: Create branch according to cpu core uarch
body:
**Description**: 

This is a preparation change for a bigger goal.  

On ARM64 CPUs with Big.Little, different cores are always the same architecture but different micro-architecture. Specifically, it is often that the little core has narrow memory buses that makes 128b load very slow.  While if we always use 64b load in our kernels, the code will run slower on big cores. As a result, we need to run different code on different cores to achieve better performance.

This change constructs a manifold that pivot based on the core micro-architecture of the current core, so that we can develop and call different kernels accordingly.

body:
Hi, team. 
I am trying to use onnx  models with quantization. 
To convert the trained model, I am using the following commands. 
```import onnx 
from onnxruntime.quantization import quantize_dynamic, QuantType

model_fp32 = 'path/to/the/model.onnx'
model_quant = 'path/to/the/model.quant.onnx'
```
